00:05:57.710 --> 00:05:58.260 align:middle line:90%
>>FITTS: Yeah.

00:05:58.260 --> 00:05:59.100 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Look what happened.

00:05:59.100 --> 00:05:59.900 align:middle line:90%
>>FITTS: Yeah.

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:05.720 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When $1 comes into the
treasury, how do you hide it?

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:07.200 align:middle line:84%
>>FITTS: Here's
the thing, George.

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:10.487 align:middle line:84%
If you look at federal accounts
and financial statements,

00:06:10.487 --> 00:06:12.320 align:middle line:84%
it's a little bit like
"The Joy of Cooking."

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:16.940 align:middle line:84%
There are hundreds and hundreds
and hundreds of recipes.

00:06:16.940 --> 00:06:19.280 align:middle line:84%
So that's why, if you want
to understand this issue,

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:23.130 align:middle line:90%
you want to focus on examples.

00:06:23.130 --> 00:06:27.230 align:middle line:84%
So for example, let's start
off with the bailouts.

00:06:27.230 --> 00:06:32.475 align:middle line:84%
At the time of $24 to
$29 trillion of bailouts,

00:06:32.475 --> 00:06:34.100 align:middle line:84%
$8 trillion dollars
would have paid off

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:36.250 align:middle line:84%
all the single-family
mortgages in the country.

00:06:36.250 --> 00:06:37.500 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Done.

00:06:37.500 --> 00:06:38.300 align:middle line:90%
>>FITTS: Right.

00:06:38.300 --> 00:06:39.680 align:middle line:90%
So whatever that--

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:41.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You got free
debt-free houses.

00:06:41.330 --> 00:06:46.370 align:middle line:84%
>>FITTS: [LAUGHS] Whatever
that $24 trillion was about,

00:06:46.370 --> 00:06:48.830 align:middle line:84%
I believe that there
was very significant

00:06:48.830 --> 00:06:51.330 align:middle line:84%
securities fraud involved
with the mortgage securities.

00:06:51.330 --> 00:06:52.130 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:53.210 align:middle line:90%
>>FITTS: Right.

00:06:53.210 --> 00:06:55.550 align:middle line:84%
And certainly the
fact that the bailouts

00:06:55.550 --> 00:06:58.940 align:middle line:84%
were three times the outstanding
single-family mortgages

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:01.700 align:middle line:84%
would indicate that that
was probably the case.

00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:05.060 align:middle line:90%
So when $1 comes in--

00:07:05.060 --> 00:07:07.550 align:middle line:84%
and remember, it can go into
an account in an agency,

00:07:07.550 --> 00:07:09.770 align:middle line:84%
or it can go into an
account in Treasury.

00:07:09.770 --> 00:07:12.740 align:middle line:84%
But the reality is that $1
doesn't go into Treasury.

00:07:12.740 --> 00:07:16.430 align:middle line:84%
It goes into a bank account
at the New York Fed, which

00:07:16.430 --> 00:07:18.890 align:middle line:90%
is depository for the Treasury.

00:07:18.890 --> 00:07:21.220 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So it's sitting
around somewhere.

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:23.290 align:middle line:90%
Somebody's got it.

00:07:23.290 --> 00:07:24.090 align:middle line:90%
>>FITTS: In theory.

00:07:24.090 --> 00:07:24.890 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: In theory.

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:25.920 align:middle line:90%
>>FITTS: In theory.

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:29.370 align:middle line:84%
So it can come in,
or it can go out.

00:07:29.370 --> 00:07:31.050 align:middle line:90%
And it can come in from taxes.

00:07:31.050 --> 00:07:36.090 align:middle line:84%
It can come in from sales and a
variety of other transactions.

00:07:36.090 --> 00:07:38.735 align:middle line:84%
Or it can come in from
selling treasury securities.

00:07:38.735 --> 00:07:39.610 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Interesting.

00:07:39.610 --> 00:07:41.250 align:middle line:84%
>>FITTS: So one of
the things we know

00:07:41.250 --> 00:07:43.800 align:middle line:84%
about the undocumentable
adjustments-- we

00:07:43.800 --> 00:07:46.590 align:middle line:84%
know that there were
probably revenues in that.

00:07:46.590 --> 00:07:49.470 align:middle line:84%
So $21 trillion
is missing, or is

00:07:49.470 --> 00:07:52.080 align:middle line:84%
undocumented, but
that $21 trillion

00:07:52.080 --> 00:07:53.500 align:middle line:90%
can be revenues and expenses.

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:56.190 align:middle line:84%
So in theory, it could be $10
trillion in and $10 trillion

00:07:56.190 --> 00:07:56.430 align:middle line:90%
out.

00:07:56.430 --> 00:07:58.847 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And wouldn't you get
interest on the $21 trillion

00:07:58.847 --> 00:08:01.290 align:middle line:90%
somewhere in some bank?

00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:04.200 align:middle line:84%
>>FITTS: Only if that was
the terms and conditions

00:08:04.200 --> 00:08:05.670 align:middle line:90%
of the account.

00:08:05.670 --> 00:08:07.980 align:middle line:84%
So we know, for
example, in Madoff--

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:11.070 align:middle line:84%
Madoff's had
extraordinary amounts

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:15.930 align:middle line:84%
of cash balances sitting
in its bank, JP Morgan.

00:08:15.930 --> 00:08:18.420 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't appear that
they were earning much, if any,

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:19.970 align:middle line:90%
interest.

00:08:19.970 --> 00:08:21.400 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Waste.

00:08:21.400 --> 00:08:22.780 align:middle line:90%
>>FITTS: No, not waste.

00:08:22.780 --> 00:08:27.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: $21 trillion dollars,
Catherine-- even if you got 3%,

00:08:27.050 --> 00:08:29.237 align:middle line:90%
you'd be making a lot of money.

00:08:29.237 --> 00:08:31.070 align:middle line:84%
>>FITTS: Well, but
here's the thing, George.

00:08:31.070 --> 00:08:33.299 align:middle line:84%
You have to look at
what they're up to.

00:08:33.299 --> 00:08:34.760 align:middle line:90%
And this is just conjecture.

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:40.250 align:middle line:84%
If I put $1 in a bank account
and part of my agreement

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:41.990 align:middle line:84%
is that I'm going to
leave that $1 there

00:08:41.990 --> 00:08:46.420 align:middle line:84%
and you're free to use it,
then that's part of the deal.

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:48.150 align:middle line:90%
I mean, if you look at--

00:08:48.150 --> 00:08:51.072 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So the
scheme widens here.

00:08:51.072 --> 00:08:53.280 align:middle line:84%
>>FITTS: Yeah, and I go back
to "The Joy of Cooking."

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:55.940 align:middle line:84%
There are hundreds and
hundreds of recipes.

00:08:55.940 --> 00:08:58.400 align:middle line:84%
I came to believe that the
HUD accounts were probably

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:01.040 align:middle line:84%
being used to launder
drug profits back.

00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:02.180 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You felt that.

00:09:02.180 --> 00:09:03.830 align:middle line:84%
>>FITTS: I believe
that, and part of it

00:09:03.830 --> 00:09:07.340 align:middle line:84%
was because of the
nature of the mortgage

00:09:07.340 --> 00:09:12.140 align:middle line:84%
fraud in the same neighborhoods
as the drugs were coming in.

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:13.070 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Drug profits.

00:09:13.070 --> 00:09:15.200 align:middle line:84%
>>FITTS: Right, so I go
back to Dillon Read here.

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:17.450 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are you talking about
illegal drugs or prescription

00:09:17.450 --> 00:09:17.900 align:middle line:90%
drugs?

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:19.490 align:middle line:84%
